  <div style="background: #f3f7f4; border-left: 7px solid #1f7a4d; padding: 18px 22px; border-radius: 12px; margin-bottom: 22px;">
    <h3 style="margin-top: 0; color: #0b3d2e;">Why This Lab Matters</h3>
    <p>
      Biology is not just about naming organisms. It is also about explaining how organisms are related.
      In this lab, you will look at several kinds of evidence biologists use to study evolution: fossils, body structures, biochemical similarities, and evolutionary trees.
    </p>
    <p style="margin-bottom: 0;">
      The main question is: <strong>How do scientists decide whether similarity points to shared ancestry?</strong>
    </p>
  </div>

  <div style="background: #eef6ff; border-left: 7px solid #2f80ed; padding: 18px 22px; border-radius: 12px; margin-bottom: 22px;">
    <h3 style="margin-top: 0; color: #1b4f8f;">The Big Idea: Same Basic Bones, Different Shapes</h3>
    <p>
      One of the most important ideas in this lab is that different animals may have the <strong>same basic skeletal parts</strong>,
      even when those parts look very different.
    </p>
    <p>
      A human arm, cat foreleg, whale flipper, and bat wing all include the same general pattern of forelimb bones:
      an upper arm bone, forearm bones, wrist bones, hand bones, and finger bones. The exact shape, size, and function of those bones may differ greatly,
      but the overall pattern is shared.
    </p>
    <p>
      That is the point. You do not need to memorize the exact shape of every carpal, metacarpal, or phalanx in a diagram.
      Instead, focus on the pattern: <strong>the same basic bones are present, but they have been modified for different functions.</strong>
    </p>
    <p style="margin-bottom: 0;">
      A bat wing is not built from a completely new set of bones. It is a modified vertebrate forelimb. The fingers are greatly elongated and support the wing membrane.
      A whale flipper is also a modified vertebrate forelimb, but it is shaped for swimming. This is why these structures are considered homologous.
    </p>
  </div>

  <div style="background: #fff1f2; border-left: 8px solid #be123c; padding: 18px 22px; border-radius: 12px; margin-bottom: 22px;">
    <h3 style="margin-top: 0; color: #9f1239;">Important Distinction: Homology vs. Analogy</h3>
    <p>
      <strong>Homologous structures</strong> share a common evolutionary origin, even if they now perform different jobs.
      A human arm, cat foreleg, whale flipper, and bat wing are homologous because they follow the same underlying forelimb pattern.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Analogous structures</strong> may perform similar jobs but do not come from the same ancestral structure.
      For example, bird wings and insect wings both allow flight, but they are not built from the same ancestral body part.
    </p>
    <p style="margin-bottom: 0;">
      So the key question is not just, “Do these structures look alike?” The better question is:
      <strong>Did these structures come from the same ancestral structure, or did they evolve similar functions separately?</strong>
    </p>
  </div>

  <div style="background: #ffffff; border: 1px solid #d8e2dc; border-radius: 14px; padding: 18px 22px; margin-bottom: 22px;">
    <h3 style="margin-top: 0; color: #0b3d2e;">Connection to Darwin</h3>
    <p>
      Darwin argued that living organisms change over time and that related organisms share common ancestry.
      Before modern DNA sequencing existed, scientists relied heavily on evidence from fossils, anatomy, development, geography, and observation.
    </p>
    <p>
      Comparative anatomy was especially important. When scientists saw the same basic bone pattern repeated in different vertebrate forelimbs,
      they interpreted that pattern as evidence that those animals inherited the structure from a shared ancestor.
    </p>
    <p style="margin-bottom: 0;">
      This lab connects directly to that tradition. You will be looking at the kinds of evidence that helped biologists build the case for evolution
      before molecular biology existed.
    </p>
  </div>

  <div style="background: #f8fafc; border-left: 7px solid #64748b; padding: 18px 22px; border-radius: 12px; margin-bottom: 22px;">
    <h3 style="margin-top: 0; color: #334155;">What Molecular Evidence Adds</h3>
    <p>
      Today, biologists can also compare molecules such as DNA, RNA, and proteins. Molecular evidence gives scientists another way to test evolutionary relationships.
    </p>
    <p>
      If two organisms have very similar DNA or protein sequences, that may suggest they share a more recent common ancestor.
      If their molecules are more different, that may suggest a more distant relationship.
    </p>
    <p style="margin-bottom: 0;">
      Molecular evidence does not replace fossils and anatomy. Instead, it adds another line of evidence.
      Strong evolutionary explanations often come from multiple sources pointing in the same direction.
    </p>
  </div>

  <div style="background: #f8fafc; border: 1px solid #d9e2ec; border-radius: 14px; padding: 18px 22px; margin-bottom: 22px;">
    <h3 style="margin-top: 0; color: #334155;">Key Terms for This Lab</h3>

    <div style="display: flex; flex-wrap: wrap; gap: 12px;">

      <div style="flex: 1 1 240px; background: #ffffff; border: 1px solid #e2e8f0; border-radius: 12px; padding: 14px;">
        <h4 style="margin-top: 0; color: #0b3d2e;">Evolution</h4>
        <p style="margin-bottom: 0;">Change in inherited traits in populations over generations.</p>
      </div>

      <div style="flex: 1 1 240px; background: #ffffff; border: 1px solid #e2e8f0; border-radius: 12px; padding: 14px;">
        <h4 style="margin-top: 0; color: #0b3d2e;">Common Ancestor</h4>
        <p style="margin-bottom: 0;">An earlier organism or population from which later groups are descended.</p>
      </div>

      <div style="flex: 1 1 240px; background: #ffffff; border: 1px solid #e2e8f0; border-radius: 12px; padding: 14px;">
        <h4 style="margin-top: 0; color: #0b3d2e;">Homologous Structures</h4>
        <p style="margin-bottom: 0;">Structures that share a common evolutionary origin, even if their shapes or functions are different today.</p>
      </div>

      <div style="flex: 1 1 240px; background: #ffffff; border: 1px solid #e2e8f0; border-radius: 12px; padding: 14px;">
        <h4 style="margin-top: 0; color: #0b3d2e;">Analogous Structures</h4>
        <p style="margin-bottom: 0;">Structures with similar functions that did not come from the same ancestral structure.</p>
      </div>

      <div style="flex: 1 1 240px; background: #ffffff; border: 1px solid #e2e8f0; border-radius: 12px; padding: 14px;">
        <h4 style="margin-top: 0; color: #0b3d2e;">Convergent Evolution</h4>
        <p style="margin-bottom: 0;">The evolution of similar traits in different lineages because they face similar challenges or selective pressures.</p>
      </div>

      <div style="flex: 1 1 240px; background: #ffffff; border: 1px solid #e2e8f0; border-radius: 12px; padding: 14px;">
        <h4 style="margin-top: 0; color: #0b3d2e;">Fossil</h4>
        <p style="margin-bottom: 0;">Preserved evidence of past life. Fossils help scientists study organisms that lived long ago.</p>
      </div>

      <div style="flex: 1 1 240px; background: #ffffff; border: 1px solid #e2e8f0; border-radius: 12px; padding: 14px;">
        <h4 style="margin-top: 0; color: #0b3d2e;">Phylogeny</h4>
        <p style="margin-bottom: 0;">The evolutionary history or relationship of an organism or group of organisms.</p>
      </div>

      <div style="flex: 1 1 240px; background: #ffffff; border: 1px solid #e2e8f0; border-radius: 12px; padding: 14px;">
        <h4 style="margin-top: 0; color: #0b3d2e;">Phylogenetic Tree</h4>
        <p style="margin-bottom: 0;">A diagram that shows a hypothesis about evolutionary relationships.</p>
      </div>

      <div style="flex: 1 1 240px; background: #ffffff; border: 1px solid #e2e8f0; border-radius: 12px; padding: 14px;">
        <h4 style="margin-top: 0; color: #0b3d2e;">Cladogram</h4>
        <p style="margin-bottom: 0;">A branching diagram that shows relationships based on shared traits.</p>
      </div>

      <div style="flex: 1 1 240px; background: #ffffff; border: 1px solid #e2e8f0; border-radius: 12px; padding: 14px;">
        <h4 style="margin-top: 0; color: #0b3d2e;">Node</h4>
        <p style="margin-bottom: 0;">A branch point on a tree. A node represents a common ancestor where lineages split.</p>
      </div>

      <div style="flex: 1 1 240px; background: #ffffff; border: 1px solid #e2e8f0; border-radius: 12px; padding: 14px;">
        <h4 style="margin-top: 0; color: #0b3d2e;">Character</h4>
        <p style="margin-bottom: 0;">A trait or feature that can be compared among organisms, such as a bone, body structure, protein, or molecular feature.</p>
      </div>

      <div style="flex: 1 1 240px; background: #ffffff; border: 1px solid #e2e8f0; border-radius: 12px; padding: 14px;">
        <h4 style="margin-top: 0; color: #0b3d2e;">Molecular Evidence</h4>
        <p style="margin-bottom: 0;">Evidence based on molecules such as DNA, RNA, proteins, or biochemical similarities.</p>
      </div>

    </div>
  </div>

  <div style="background: #fffaf0; border-left: 7px solid #c58a1a; padding: 18px 22px; border-radius: 12px; margin-bottom: 22px;">
    <h3 style="margin-top: 0; color: #8a5a00;">Reading Trees: A Simple Reminder</h3>
    <p>
      When reading a phylogenetic tree or cladogram, do not focus only on which organisms are beside each other on the page.
      Instead, look for the most recent common ancestor.
    </p>
    <p style="margin-bottom: 0;">
      Two organisms are more closely related if they share a more recent common ancestor. Branches can often be rotated around nodes without changing the meaning of the tree.
      The branching pattern matters more than the exact left-right position.
    </p>
